$frontmatter {
  title: Eval & Trace
  description: In-memory trace capture with lutum-trace and evaluation helpers with lutum-eval.
  tags = ["eval", "trace", "testing"]
}

"#": Eval & Trace

"intro" = ```markdown
`lutum-trace` captures in-memory spans and events from LLM turns. `lutum-eval` builds evaluation
helpers on top of captured traces: synchronous `PureEval`, async `Eval`, and live `Probe` hooks.
```

"toc".$toc = true

@ "trace-setup" {
  "##": Trace Setup

  "body" = ```markdown
Add the crates and set up the tracing subscriber:
```

  "toml-example" = ```toml
[dependencies]
lutum-trace = "0.1.0"
tracing-subscriber = { version = "0.3", features = ["registry"] }
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use tracing_subscriber::layer::SubscriberExt as _;

// Build a subscriber with the capture layer
let subscriber = tracing_subscriber::registry()
    .with(lutum_trace::layer());

// You can also compose with other layers (stdout, json, etc.)
let subscriber = tracing_subscriber::registry()
    .with(lutum_trace::layer())
    .with(tracing_subscriber::fmt::layer());
```

}

@ "capture" {
  "##": Capturing a Turn

  "body" = ```markdown
Wrap any async block with `lutum_trace::capture(...)` to get back the result plus a
`TraceSnapshot`:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::Session;
use tracing::instrument::WithSubscriber as _;

let collected = lutum_trace::capture(
    async {
        let mut session = Session::new(llm.clone());
        session.push_user("Say hello in one sentence.");
        let result = session.text_turn().collect().await?;
        Ok::<_, Box<dyn std::error::Error>>(result.assistant_text().to_string())
    }
    .with_subscriber(subscriber),
)
.await;

// Access the result
let text = collected.output.unwrap();

// Inspect the trace
if let Some(turn) = collected.trace.span("llm_turn") {
    println!("request_id = {:?}", turn.field("request_id"));
    println!("finish_reason = {:?}", turn.field("finish_reason"));
}
```

  "body-2" = ```markdown
`Collected<T>` has two fields:
- `output: T` — the return value of the wrapped async block
- `trace: TraceSnapshot` — structured snapshot of all spans and events

`TraceSnapshot::span(name)` returns the first span with the given name. Each span exposes
`field(key)` for accessing recorded field values and `events()` for child events.
```

}

@ "raw-capture" {
  "##": Raw Capture

  "body" = ```markdown
`lutum_trace::capture_raw(...)` captures both a structured snapshot and the raw trace entries as a
`Vec<TraceEntry>`. Useful for debugging or custom analysis:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
let collected = lutum_trace::capture_raw(
    my_async_block.with_subscriber(subscriber)
).await;

let trace: &TraceSnapshot = &collected.trace;
let raw: &RawTraceSnapshot = &collected.raw;
```

}

@ "pure-eval" {
  "##": PureEval — Synchronous Evaluation

  "body" = ```markdown
`PureEval` is a synchronous evaluation trait over a captured trace plus an application-specific
artifact:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum_eval::{PureEval, Scored, Score};

struct ResponseLengthEval;

impl PureEval for ResponseLengthEval {
    type Artifact = String;   // the artifact type (e.g. assistant text)
    type Report = usize;      // the report type (e.g. character count)

    fn evaluate(
        &self,
        trace: &TraceSnapshot,
        artifact: &Self::Artifact,
    ) -> Scored<Self::Report> {
        let len = artifact.len();
        let score = Score::new((len.min(500) as f32 / 500.0 * 100.0) as u8);
        Scored { report: len, score }
    }
}
```

}

@ "eval-trait" {
  "##": Eval — Async Evaluation

  "body" = ```markdown
`Eval` is the async variant. It receives a `Lutum` context in addition to the trace and artifact,
which lets the evaluator run its own LLM calls (e.g. an LLM-as-judge):
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum_eval::{Eval, Scored, Score};
use lutum::Lutum;
use async_trait::async_trait;

struct LlmJudge;

#[async_trait]
impl Eval for LlmJudge {
    type Artifact = String;
    type Report = String;

    async fn evaluate(
        &self,
        llm: &Lutum,
        trace: &TraceSnapshot,
        artifact: &Self::Artifact,
    ) -> Scored<Self::Report> {
        let prompt = format!("Rate this response 1-10 and explain: {artifact}");
        let result = llm
            .completion(prompt)
            .collect()
            .await
            .expect("judge call failed");

        let text = result.text.clone();
        let score = Score::new(extract_score(&text));
        Scored { report: text, score }
    }
}
```

}

@ "probe" {
  "##": Probe — Live Evaluation

  "body" = ```markdown
`Probe` hooks into a live turn via `collect_with(...)`. It observes streaming events in real time,
making it useful for latency monitoring, streaming quality checks, or live dashboards:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum_eval::Probe;

struct FirstTokenTimer {
    start: std::time::Instant,
}

impl Probe for FirstTokenTimer {
    fn on_text_delta(&mut self, delta: &str) {
        let latency = self.start.elapsed();
        println!("First token at {latency:?}: {delta:?}");
    }
}

let result = session
    .text_turn()
    .collect_with(FirstTokenTimer { start: std::time::Instant::now() })
    .await?;
```

}

@ "eval-runner" {
  "##": lutum-eval-runner — k-Metrics

  "body" = ```markdown
`lutum-eval-runner` provides `pass_at_k` and `pass_hat_k` for measuring model reliability across
multiple trials:
```

  "toml-example" = ```toml
[dependencies]
lutum-eval-runner = "0.1.0"
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum_eval_runner::{pass_at_k, KMetric};

// Run 10 trials of the same task
let metric: KMetric = pass_at_k(
    10,    // k — number of trials
    1,     // n — number of successes required
    || async {
        let result = session.text_turn().collect().await?;
        let passes = result.assistant_text().contains("correct answer");
        Ok(passes)
    },
)
.await?;

println!("pass@10 = {:.2}", metric.rate);
```

}
